1 in t his state. The parolee shall, after arrest, be immediately
2 incarcerated in the nearest county jail, intermediate sanctions
3 facility, or a Department of Corrections facility to await action by
4 the Governor or the Pardon and Parole Board as to whether the parole
5 will be revoked. Parole time shall cease to run after the issuance
6 of a warrant for arrest by the Department of Corrections, and earned
7 credits shall not be accrued during any period of time when the
8 parolee is incarcerated pending revocation action by the Governor or
9 the Pardon and Parole Board. Pursuant to the provisions of this
10 subsection:
11 1. The Governor shall have the power and authority to revoke
12 parole granted by the Governor and file the certificate of
13 revocation with the Secretary of State; and
14 2. The Pardon and Parole Board, by majority vote, shall have
15 the power and authority to revoke parole granted by the Pardon and
16 Parole Board and file the certificate of revocation with the
17 Secretary of State.
18 B. Any parolee determined to have violated any terms or
19 conditions of parole by the supervising parole officer may be given
20 the option, at the discretion of the Department of Corrections, to
21 be placed in an intermediate sanctions facility for disciplinary
22 sanction and programmatic services in lieu of revocation or when
23 revocation action by the Governor or the Pardon and Parole Board is
24 deemed unnecessary for the nature of the violation. Any parolee for
